<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-third" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>What is a Differential Equation?</title>

  <p>
    Derivatives are used to model changing situations! And things are changing all around us!
  </p>

 <figure xml:id="video-what-is-de">
  <caption>What is a Differential Equation?</caption>
 <video youtube="hjelg90Tv7Q" width="80%" play-at="embed" preview="default"/>
</figure>

<video youtube="hjelg90Tv7Q">
  <title> What is a Differential Equation? </title>
</video>

<video youtube="hjelg90Tv7Q" width="80%" play-at="embed" preview="default"/>



  <example xml:id="ex-setup-population-de">
    <title>Setting Up a Differential Equation</title>
    <p>
      Come up with an equation that models the following situation: <em>The rate of change of a population <m>P(t)</m> (where <m>t</m> is time in years) is proportional to the current population. The constant of proportionality is 3.</em>
    </p>
    <hint>
      <p>
        The rate of change of <m>P</m> is the derivative with respect to time, which is <m>\frac{dP}{dt}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        "The rate of change of <m>P(t)</m> is..." translates to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = \ldots</m> What can you put on the right-hand side of the equation to represent that it is proportional to the current population, where the constant of proportionality is 3?
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The answer is <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>. The left-hand side <m>\frac{dP}{dt}</m> denotes <em>the rate of change of the population</em>. The right-hand side, <m>3P</m>, expresses a quantity that is proportional to <m>P</m>, with a proportionality constant of 3.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    In the previous example, you just set up a <em>differential equation</em>. We often want to take this a step further and find a solution. In this case, that would be a population function <m>P(t)</m> that satisfies the conditions of the previous example (where the rate of change of the population is proportional to itself, with proportionality constant equaling 3).
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-solve-population-de">
    <title>Solving a Differential Equation</title>
    <p>
      Can you think of a function <m>P(t)</m> that solves the previous differential equation?
    </p>
    <hint>
      <p>
        We are looking for a function <m>P(t)</m> whose derivative equals <m>3P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        First try solving the simpler question: Find a function <m>P(t)</m> whose derivative is itself. That is, it satisfies <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = P</m>.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We want to solve the differential equation <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>. Let's first consider the simpler equation <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = P</m>. A solution <m>P(t)</m> is one whose derivative is itself. Recall that the famous exponential function <m>P(t) = e^t</m> has this property!
      </p>
      <p>
        Let's modify this to solve <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>. How do we modify <m>e^t</m> so that a 3 comes in front when differentiating <m>P(t)</m>? The chain rule should come to mind! Indeed, if we set <m>P(t) = e^{3t}</m>, we find <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3e^{3t}</m>, which equals <m>3P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        So <m>P(t) = e^{3t}</m> solves <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>. Can you think of any others?
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <definition xml:id="def-differential-equation">
    <title>Differential Equation</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A <term>differential equation</term> is an equation involving a function <m>y(x)</m>, its derivatives <m>y', y'', y''', \ldots</m>, and an independent variable <m>x</m>. 
      </p>
      <p>
        The <term>order</term> of a differential equation is the highest derivative appearing.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
<p>
  A differential equation involving only derivative with respect to only one variable (as opposed to partial derivatives) is 
called an <term>ordinary differential equation (ODE)</term>.
</p>
  <p>
    Here are three examples of ODEs, along with their orders:
    <md>
      <mrow>\frac{dP}{dt} \amp= 3P \quad \leadsto \text{1st order}</mrow>
      <mrow>\frac{d^2y}{dx^2} + x^2 \amp= \frac{dy}{dx} e^x \quad \leadsto \text{2nd order}</mrow>
      <mrow>y''' + y''y + \sin(y') \amp= x \quad \leadsto \text{3rd order}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <remark xml:id="rem-notation">
    <title>Notation</title>
    <p>
      We adopt both the prime notation <m>y'</m> and Leibniz notation <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> to denote the derivative of <m>y</m> with respect to <m>t</m>. These are equivalent and will be used interchangeably throughout.
    </p>
    <p>
      In <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m>, <m>t</m> is the independent variable and <m>P</m> is the dependent variable. The actual letters we use for the variable will vary. In the last example, <m>y''' + y''y + \sin(y') = x</m>, it is implied that <m>y</m> is the dependent variable and <m>x</m> is the independent variable.
    </p>
  </remark>

  <definition xml:id="def-general-solution-population">
    <title>Solution to the Population Growth Model</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A simple model of a population <m>P(t)</m> is that the rate of change is proportional to the population. So <m>P(t)</m> satisfies:
        <me>\frac{dP}{dt} = kP.</me>
        The <term>general solution</term> to this differential equation is:
        <me>P(t) = Ce^{kt},</me>
        where varying over any real number for <m>C</m> gives all possible solutions.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    Try verifying this by differentiating <m>P(t) = Ce^{kt}</m>:
  </p>

  <solution>
    <title>Verification</title>
    <p>
      By the chain rule, <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = kCe^{kt} = kP</m>. <m>\checkmark</m>
    </p>
     </solution>
    <p>
      Some examples of specific solutions:
      <md>
        <mrow>C = 2\text{:} \amp\quad P(t) = 2e^{kt}</mrow>
        <mrow>C = -3\text{:} \amp\quad P(t) = -3e^{kt}</mrow>
        <mrow>C = 0\text{:} \amp\quad P(t) = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \frac{dP}{dt} = kP \checkmark</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
 

  <p>
    With the proper <term>initial conditions</term> we obtain a <term>specific solution</term> to a differential equation.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-initial-condition">
    <title>Applying an Initial Condition</title>
    <p>
      Suppose a population <m>P</m> satisfies <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 2P</m>, and the initial population at <m>t = 0</m> is <m>P(0) = 200</m>. Find the solution <m>P(t)</m>.
    </p>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The general solution with <m>k = 2</m> is:
        <me>P(t) = Ce^{2t}.</me>
        Applying the initial condition <m>P(0) = 200</m>:
        <me>200 = Ce^{2 \cdot 0} = C \cdot 1 \implies C = 200.</me>
        So the specific solution is:
        <me>P(t) = 200e^{2t}.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="ex-setup-des">
    <title>Setting Up Differential Equations</title>
    <p>
      Set up the differential equations that model the following situations.
    </p>
    <p>
      (1) The rate of change of a velocity <m>v</m> of a car is proportional to the cube of <m>v</m>.
    </p>
    <solution>
      <p><me>\frac{dv}{dt} = kv^3</me></p>
    </solution>
    <p>
      (2) <em>Newton's law of cooling</em> states that the time rate of change of a temperature <m>T</m> of an object is proportional to the difference between <m>T</m> and the surrounding temperature <m>A</m>.
    </p>
    <solution>
      <p><me>\frac{dT}{dt} = k(T - A)</me></p>
    </solution>
    <p>
      (3) The slope of the tangent line of a graph of <m>y(x)</m> at the point <m>(x, y)</m> is equal to the square root of the product of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
    </p>
    <solution>
      <p><me>\frac{dy}{dx} = \sqrt{xy}</me></p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <p>
    To verify that <m>y(x)</m> is a solution to a differential equation, you must plug in <m>y</m> and its relevant derivatives into both sides of the equation and verify they equal each other.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="ex-verify-solution">
    <title>Verifying a Solution</title>
    <p>
      Verify that <m>y(x) = Ce^{-x^3}</m> is a solution to <m>y' + 3x^2 y = 0</m>.
    </p>
    <hint>
      <p>
        Compute <m>y'</m>. Then plug the expressions for <m>y</m> and <m>y'</m> into the equation and check if the left and right sides are equal.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution>
      <p>
        We compute:
        <ul>
          <li><m>y(x) = Ce^{-x^3}</m></li>
          <li>
            <p><m>y'(x) = -3x^2 Ce^{-x^3}</m></p>
            <solution>
              <title>Explanation: Computing <m>y'</m></title>
              <p>
                We find <m>y'</m> by using the chain rule on <m>e^{-x^3}</m>, which is a composition of <m>e^x</m> (outside function) with <m>-x^3</m> (the inside function). The derivative of the inside function equals <m>-3x^2</m>, which is why this expression is multiplied out in front when differentiating.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        Plugging into <m>y' + 3x^2 y = 0</m>:
        <me>y' + 3x^2 y = -3x^2 Ce^{-x^3} + 3x^2 \cdot Ce^{-x^3} = 0 = \text{RHS.} \checkmark</me>
        Therefore <m>y(x) = Ce^{-x^3}</m> is a solution.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

</section>
